A view of the Intensive Care Unit treating COVID-19 coronavirus patients in the Gilberto Novaes Hospital in Brazil. AFP/Michael Dantas JOHANNESBURG - New research shows that nearly 20-percent of COVID-19 patients develop mental health issues within three months of diagnosis. These include depression, anxiety, and dementia. READ: 1/5 of the world won't have the COVID vaccine until 2022: study Researchers evaluated the health records of 69-million people in the United States, which included over 62,000 people diagnosed with COVID-19. Doctors have long suspected that COVID-19 was linked to higher rates of mental health problems.